ce:section.ce:para:
Photocatalytic activity of CQDs was tested in visible light, typically the electrode was submerged in the dye (Methylene Blue) solution of a conc. of 2 mg/L. Initially, the CQDs-coated fabric was dipped in the dye solution under the dark condition until the adsorption was stopped (120 min). The concentration of the dye solution after adsorption was considered as a reference or initial concentration. Afterward, visible light was turned on, and a decrease in the concentration of dye due to photocatalysis was recorded every 10 min, for a total of 120 min. The percentage reduction in absorbance of UV-vis spectra of dye solution at 665 nm (λmax) was noted as the photocatalytic efficiency of the electrode. Furthermore, during the photocatalysis test, the solution was kept constant stirring with a stirrer, to confirm the homogeneous degradation. The CQDs showed a photocatalytic degradation of 80 % (Fig. 10a
                           ), which is comparable to the photocatalytic activity of other metal oxides-based catalysts. Owing to the low band gap of developed CQDs, visible light absorbance and photo-generated excitons are relatively higher than commonly high bandgap photocatalysts like TiO2. The greater photocatalytic degradation of CQDs is referred to the broad light absorption spectrum of CQDs, and associated charge generation. This charge generated essentially produces O2
                           − and nascent oxygen species (called reactive oxygen species), which readily oxidize the dye molecule [45]. The role of such photogenerated excitons in CQDs is also utilized as a sensitizer, where the photogenerated excitons are collected for the current generation [46].
